","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cárthaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Cárthach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘loving’. This was the name of a ruling family in Munster. In Ireland major branches were distinguished by the following epithets: <i>mór</i> ‘great’ in Kerry, <i>riabhach</i> ‘brindled’ in Carbery, west Cork."]}]},{"name":"Donald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Domhnall . The final <i>-d</i> of the Anglicized form derives partly from misinterpretation by English speakers of the Gaelic pronunciation, and partly from association with Germanic-origin names such as   Ronald .  This name is strongly associated with clan Macdonald, the clan of the medieval Lords of the Isles, but is now also widely used by families with no Scottish connections."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Glas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Blasius</i>, probably from <i>blaesus</i> ‘lisping’.  See  <b>Blaise</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vlasi","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Blasius</i>, probably from <i>blaesus</i> ‘lisping’.  See  <b>Blaise</b>   ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Donald Glas I Maccarthy was born about 1320, in Carbury, County Kildare, Ireland, his father, Donal Caomh, \"the Handsome\", Mac Carthy Reagh, Prince of Carbery, was 26 and his mother, carew, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Julia O'Cromin. He died in 1366, at the age of 47."},"et":{"ABT 1320–1366":"umbes 1320–1366","1320–1366":"1320–1366","–Male":"Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1340–1414":"1340–1414","1295–1320":"1295–1320","1297–Female":"1297–Surnud","1414":"1414","ABT 1320":"umbes 1320","1366":"1366","1320":"1320","1297":"1297","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","Carbury, County Kildare, Ireland":"Carbury, County Kildare, Iirimaa","Kilbrittain Castle, County Cork, Ireland":"Kilb